The Annual GIBBY/RAIDER Open golf outing to benefit the Decatur Athletic Boosters will be held on Sunday, August 16, 2020 at Lake Cora Golf Course in Paw Paw. The 18-hole golf scramble begins at 9:00 a.m. The fee ($50 per person/ $200 per foursome) includes 18 holes of golf with cart, water, pop, burgers, brats and hot dogs all day long. There will also be opportunities to win prizes. Please contact Julie Leighton at 269-436-0358 for more information. There is additional information in the picture attached.

post_text:
Food Distribution at Decatur Public Schools

The last day of food distribution at Decatur Public Schools is June 5. However, we’ll continue a similar program beginning July 1 through the second week of August. Food distribution will be either once or twice per week at the same location (Jr. Sr. High School parking lot). Please answer this brief survey to help us determine the number of meals to prepare: https://forms.gle/buG9ZggGYkrvk7iy6

El ultimo dia de distribución de comida en las Escuelas Públicas de Decatur será el 5 de junio. Sin embargo, continuaremos con un programa similar comenzando el 1 de julio hasta la segunda semana de agosto. La distribución será o una o dos veces por semana en el mismo lugar (el estacionamiento de Jr. Sr. High School). Favor de contestar esta encuesta para ayudarnos a determinar el número de comidas para preparar: https://forms.gle/buG9ZggGYkrvk7iy6

Decatur Public Schools

Kindergarten 2020-2021

Registration will be available on our website at:
www.raiderpride.org

Children who will be five years old on or before September 1, 2020

Parent(s) and or Guardian
Please fill out the Student Information Sheet located on our website before June 5, 2020. All other required forms will be distributed and collected in August 2020.

Before your child attends Kindergarten, the following documents are required:
• Original Birth Certificate
• Current Immunization Records (All required doses of DTP, Hep B series, MMR series, Polio and Varicella)
• Two Proofs of Residency (Tax Statement, Home Purchase Agreement, Home Rental Agreement, Utility Bill, Insurance Forms)

For any further questions, please contact our office on Wednesday mornings.
Office hours are from 8am-12pm
(269)423-6954

Grading and Assessment Plan for Decatur Jr. Sr. High School

For the remainder of the academic year Decatur Jr. Sr. High School will be adhering to the “No Educational Harm” philosophy being used by many schools in the state of Michigan. With this concept, the grade earned by a student in a class as of March 13 will serve as the lowest possible score the student can earn for the second semester. All work assigned by teachers for the remainder of the year may only be used to boost existing grades.

All students will be given the opportunity to redo and submit any assignment and activity previously assigned during the 3rd marking period in order to improve their current grade. Any request to…

Continuity of Learning Plan

Decatur Public Schools is ready to start our Continuity of Learning Plan. This plan explains how the district will provide education to our students while our buildings are closed. The plan is listed on our webpage at www.raiderpride.org.

Davis Elementary will be distributing learning packets starting Tuesday, April 21 at the same time as food distribution from 12:00-1:00 in the Jr/Sr High parking lot. If you are unable to pick up your packet during this time, packets will also be available for pickup in the Davis lobby area on Wednesdays from 8:00 - 12:00 and Fridays from 1:00 - 3:00. post_text:
Dear Raider Families and Friends:

On April 2nd, Governor Whitmer signed Executive Order 2020-35, which orders all K-12 school buildings closed for the remainder of the school year — unless restrictions are lifted — and ensures continuing of learning by setting guidelines for remote learning. The administration and staff of Decatur Public Schools have been working on a “Continuity of Learning Plan” that will deliver instruction to our students. None of this instruction will be at the school and it will not be face to face. We will send the plan to the Van Buren Intermediate School District for review by April 17th. The plan, to be implemented no later than April 28th, will include distance… More

The English/Spanish version of the survey can be found at: https://forms.gle/BC2fkgmLu3pf15xk6

post_text:
Over 350 students received meals last week! Each student had plenty of food and milk throughout the weekend and Monday! Thanks so much to our lunch ladies and Dylan Peyton for making this all possible! It's an incredible thing that they do to help our families through this tough time. As always, stay positive and stay safe.
Patrick

post_text: On February 17, the Decatur High School ELA classes were treated to a special learning event. One of our graduates from Decatur, Amanda Rotach Lamkin (class of 1999), acclaimed writer and publisher, shared her writing and publishing experiences with the ninth through twelfth graders in four sessions on Monday. Not only did Amanda teach students her take on four points that transcend the writing process, she also suggested the ways in which the process can be applied to strategies which students can use to keep focused on for all of their passions to succeed. Amanda's presentation was insightful, quirky, and relatable to all of the students. Amanda created an amazing experience for DHS students. She championed the truism that the possibilities for reaching dreams does not matter where a person comes from but how one can persevere to make dreams happen.

Award of Excellence winners at Decatur Jr. Sr. High School last week were Braydon Ross, Ismael Pena, Michael Prieto, Bernece Miller and Alexandria Jones.

Braydon demonstrated excellence by improving his NWEA math score by 18 points, more than any other high school student. Ismael and Bernece demonstrated excellence by increasing their NWEA reading scores by 40 points, more than any other junior high student. Michael also demonstrated excellence on the NWEA math assessment when he improved his score by 25 points. Finally, Alexandria earned her Award of Excellence for demonstrating kindness and a great deal of assistance to a guest teacher. The students and staff at Decatur Jr. Sr. High school would like to thank these individuals for helping to make our school excellent! Proud Raiders Intentionally Demonstrate Excellence!

post_text: Last week special education teacher Karen Nuckels received a $500 Strengthening Schools grant from Midwest Energy and Communications. Karen applied for this grant on behalf of her students. The money from this grant will be used to purchase a commercial coffee maker, snacks, and supplies for the business project being conducted by the students. Each week students from Karen’s class will travel around the district and sell coffee, water, and snacks to our staff. They will develop communication skills, practice interacting socially, learn how to handle money, and benefit in many other ways from operating their own business. Congratulations to Karen and her students for receiving this grant and best of luck with your business!

Award of Excellence winners at Decatur Jr. Sr. High School include Daniel Northrup, Morgan McLouth, Braydon Grissom, Miragia Avery, Sarah Pease, MiKayla Dierickx, and Hunter Slavings. Daniel, MiKayla, and Morgan demonstrated excellence by taking first place in the Patriot’s Pen essay contest in their respective age groups. Braydon was nominated for excellence by a staff member who observed him cleaning up a mess in the hallway without being asked. Miragia was nominated by a teacher who observed her showing compassion and support to a middle school student who was having difficulties. Sarah was nominated by one of her students for teaching quality lessons and taking a genuine interest in her students. Hunter demonstrated excellence when he stopped and pulled out the car of a classmate that was stuck in a ditch. The students and staff of Decatur Jr. Sr. High School thanks these individuals for helping to make our school excellent! Proud Raiders Intentionally Demonstrate
Excellence!

post_text:
Gavin is a track and cross country athlete.
>>>>>>> master
His best memory of the year was during his last race. He ran a personal best of 23.23 on the toughest course all year.
He says that the hardest part of being a student-athlete is balancing exam weeks and the weeks that you are drained from practice and meets.
His kinda went both ways. He started off the season running really well in the 23-minute range for each meet, then he hit a slump once it got really hot out. He started running in the 28-minute range and didn't know if he would be able to make it back down to the 23-minute range again. He persevered and on the last race, ran a personal best of 23 minutes and 23 seconds.
text:
Gavin is a track and cross country athlete.
His best memory of the year was during his last race. He ran a personal best of 23.23 on the toughest course all year.
He says that the hardest part of being a student-athlete is balancing exam weeks and the weeks that you are drained from practice and meets.
His kinda went both ways. He started off the season running really well in the 23-minute range for each meet, then he hit a slump once it got really hot out. He started running in the 28-minute range and didn't know if he would be able to make it back down to the 23-minute range again. He persevered and on the last race, ran a personal best of 23 minutes and 23 seconds.

post_text: The Davis Book Fair will run from November 4 through November 8. The fair will be open during parent/teacher conferences from 1:00-8:pm as well. The Book Fair will be held in the Davis Library, and all the money raised will go directly to the Davis Library for new books. Students at Davis will visit the Book Fair during their regular library time. Flyers will be going home soon. If you have any questions, please contact Ms. Moser at 423-6950.
